observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the City Mayor direct the:

CAD to prepare the necessary adjusting entry to correct the misclassification of Inventory accounts amounting to P2,719,748.82 and furnish the COA a copy of the corresponding JEV;

GSO to conduct physical count of inventories on a semestral basis and prepare the corresponding RPCI according to the prescribed format pursuant to Annex 48, Volume 2 and Section 124, Chapter 7, Volume 1 of the MNGAS for LGUs;

GSO to prepare SSMI and submit to the CAD, on a weekly basis, for recording the supplies and materials used as required in Section 43, Chapter 2, Volume 2 of the said Manual; and

CAD to record inventory related expenses based on SSMI submitted by the GSO in pursuant to said Section 43 of the Manual.

We recommended the Management to require the City Assessor to:

Re-assess the 6,449 RPUs based on the sufficient documentary evidence provided by its tax payers whether these are to be retained as exempted property and to return to the Assessment Roll those properties that are taxable, for proper assessment and collection of the corresponding RPT;

Provide the Audit Team with the revised and updated List of the Real Properties Exempted from Real Property Taxes upon re-assessment together with its supporting documents; and;

Henceforth, strictly comply with Sections 206 and 234 of RA No. 7160 and Section 16 of the Muntinlupa Tax Code in determining the property to be exempted from RPT and strictly use the codes provided by Section 2 (D), Chapter VI of the BLGF Manual on Real Property Appraisal and Assessment Operations.

We recommended the Management to –

Maximize the use of LDRRMF of the City and fully implement the planned PPAs to attain the City’s preparedness, response and recovery from the impacts of natural and man-made disasters efficiently and effectively;

Require the City Accountant, in coordination with the City Budget Officer and head of MDDRM, to reconcile the balances of the Continuing Appropriations and Special Trust Fund of the LDDRMF recorded in the book of accounts to reflect the actual available funds and to avoid confusion and difference between the reports of CAD and CBMD;

Henceforth, strictly comply with Section 305 (a) of RA No. 7160, Sections 6.2 and 6.5 of NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-01 and Sections 4.4 and 5.1.15 of COA Circular 
No. 2012-002

We recommended and the City Mayor agreed to:
Require the CTO and OCA to coordinate with the Management Information Systems (MIS) Office to resolve the identified system’s defects in the RPTAS, such as:
The generation of the Summary of Receivables per Barangay only without the corresponding list of taxpayers and their tax dues;
The prolonged duration required for the generation of reports and noted errors encountered during the report generation from the RPTAS;
Inconsistencies between reported data in the RPTAS-generated Real Property Tax Delinquency Listing and individual statements of account for tax dues;
Direct the CTO and OCA to reconcile inconsistencies in the Assessment Rolls and Real Property Tax Deficiency Listings by generating the list of taxpayers with outstanding tax dues for the year and match it with the master list or assessment roll;
Compel the CTO to submit the reconciled summary of receivables, including the list of taxpayers and their corresponding tax dues, to the CAD for necessary adjustments in the accrual of receivables;
Require the CTO to review the RPTAS-generated Real Property Tax Delinquency Listing and reconcile it with the OCA’s Assessment Roll to identify discrepancies, particularly in assessed values, which serve as the basis for tax computation; and
Require the CTO in coordination with MIS Office to re-orient personnel in-charge of the RPTAS, particularly in report generation, to ensure its full and effective utilization.

We recommended and the City Mayor agreed to require the –
CAD:
To regularly monitor the individual balances of the Due from Officers and Employees and henceforth, regularly initiate collection from concerned personnel;
To conduct reconciliation between the List of Employees with outstanding balances recorded in the subsidiary ledgers (SL) and the Master List of Employees from City Human Resources Management Department (CHRMD), and to demand payment or settlement of receivables from concerned active personnel, and withhold any claims/salaries until full settlement is made;
To demand payment of any unpaid balances from the separated employees;
To exert effort in locating the lacking records for the identification of those unidentified individuals with balances;
To assess the condition and collectability of the Due from Officers and Employees account, properly recognize the extent of the doubtful accounts, and consider the provision of its Allowance for Impairment before requesting for the write off of the dormant accounts in compliance with COA Circular No. 2023-008; and
CHRMD to regularly update and maintain accurate records of the employee’s contact information to facilitate future collection efforts against employees with outstanding balances.

We recommended and the City Mayor agreed to:
Create an Inventory Committee, which will include a representative from the CAD, to conduct the regular physical count/inventory of all the City’s inventories, including the preparation, approval, reconciliation and submission of the corresponding RPCI;
Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count every semester as required, reconcile any noted discrepancies with the balances of Inventory in the books of accounts;
Require the CAD to prepare and maintain SLCs for each type of supply and other inventory items recorded under Inventories account;
Direct the CHO, GSO, and the Social Services Department (SSD) to:
Ensure that all issuances of inventory items are with duly accomplished and approved RIS prior to its release to end-users or requesting parties;
Prepare and submit SSMI to CAD on a regular basis, for recording of issued inventories;
Maintain and regularly update their respective Stock Cards (SCs);
Require OsMun to:
Instruct the concerned department heads to keep the records of issuances up to date and to regularly submit the Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (RSMI)/Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) to CAD for recording and reconciliation;
Submit pertinent documents relative to donated inventories and supplies to CAD and GSO for proper monitoring and recording of inventories; and
Direct the GSO to assign a stock number for each inventory items or supplies used by the City to ensure uniform stock number for easier monitoring and recording.

We recommended and the City Mayor agreed to require the LSB to:
Conduct proper and thorough planning and budgeting of SEF target PPAs, based on past financial data and the absorptive capacity of the School Division Office and ECED to implement their targets and to come out with a more realistic budget;
Prepare a catch-up plan for the continuation and implementation of unimplemented PPAs for CY 2024, and reprogram the same for the succeeding year through the issuance of supplemental budget;
Facilitate the preparation and submission of the required documents/reports needed for the infrastructure projects and procurement of goods and services to ensure the implementation of planned PPAs; and
henceforth, establish a monitor mechanism on the implementation of the approved PPAs and the utilization of its budget to fully support the education of those in public schools.

We recommended and the City Mayor agreed to instruct the:
CPDO to:
Closely monitor the proper implementation of the partially and unimplemented LCCAP-related PPAs;
Require Implementing Offices to regularly submit Status of Implementation and ensure timely submission of reports;
Conduct VAA at least every two-years to reflect the changing social, economic and environmental conditions and emerging issues on climate change;
Implementing Offices to:
Regularly submit their status of implementation of their respective tagged LCCAP-related PPAs;
Evaluate whether the identified LCCAP-related PPAs were still relevant and reflect the changing environmental conditions and emerging issues on climate change; and
Consider their absorptive capacity in the implementation of targets and include only the LCCAP tagged PPAs that they can accomplished with the year.

We recommended that the Management direct the LSB to:

Submit a Board Resolution authorizing the Chairperson of the LSB to augment any item in the approved annual budget from savings in other items within the same expense class of their respective appropriations in pursuant to Section 336 of RA No. 7160;

Submit the revised APP and the corresponding PPMP for the changes in the annual budget for CY 2023 to this Office in pursuant to Section 7.2 of The 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and Item 2.4 of LBC No. 112, BOM for LGUs, for our further audit and evaluation.

We recommend that the City Mayor require the Head, Office of the Dagdag Puhunan to:

Transfer to the individual accounts the compulsory/ weekly savings of each borrower/clients immediately; and


Compute the total compulsory/weekly savings for those who are delinquent and apply such payment to the unpaid balance. The excess if there are any, should be returned to the borrowers/ clients;

We recommended the Management to –

Record the purchases of inventories as assets and only recognize expense upon issuance of the same;


Prepare and maintain Stock Cards and the Supplies Ledger Cards;

Conduct physical count of inventories at least twice a year and prepare the necessary RPCI and reconcile the same with the accounting books; and

Henceforth, strictly comply with the provisions of MNGAS for LGUs.

We recommended that the Management –

Require the SDO to fully implement PPAs with target completion date within the year;

Consider to reprogram the budget for the provisions of textbooks and instructional materials to other priority PPAs as identified in DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017 and 2020;

Henceforth, strictly comply with the provisions of DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017, in ensuring a more strategic and efficient utilization of resources for priority programs and projects chargeable against SEF.

We recommended the Management to –

Maximize the use of LDRRMF of the City and fully implement the planned PPAs to attain the City’s preparedness, response and recovery from the impacts of natural and man-made disasters efficiently and effectively;

Provide a copy of the appropriation ordinance on the disbursement of Special Trust Fund and LDRRMFIP in CY 2022;

Require the City Accountant, in coordination with the City Budget Officer and head of MDDRM, to reconcile the balances of the Continuing Appropriations and Special Trust Fund of the LDDRMF recorded in the book of accounts to reflect the actual available funds and to avoid confusion and difference between the reports of CAD and CBMD;

Including the review and updating of the LDRRMFIP indicating the PPAs to be charged against the LDRRMF Special Trust Fund before making any disbursements; and

Henceforth, strictly comply with Section 305 (a) of RA No. 7160, Sections 6.2 and 6.5 of NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-01 and Sections 4.4 and 5.1.15 of COA Circular 
No. 2012-002

We recommended the Management to –

Submit the renewal contract for the storage and handling of vaccines in CY 2022;

Immediately demand from the service provider to refund the amount of P538,051.29, and coordinate with the BIR for the recovery/application of the remitted amount of P384,322.35 due to exempt transactions

