We recommended that the City Mayor require the Head, Dagdag Puhunan Office to:
Provide bonded cashiers/collectors deputized to collect amortization and instruct them to immediately issue the corresponding ORs;
Transfer to the individual accounts the compulsory/weekly savings of each borrower/client immediately;
Compute the total compulsory/weekly savings for those who are delinquent and apply such savings to the unpaid balance. The excess if there is any, should be returned to the borrower/client; and
Stop the practice of maintaining a mother account for the compulsory/weekly savings and require the mandatory opening of individual accounts.

We recommended that the City Mayor require:
The City Treasurer to -
Adopt measures and strategies on how to improve collection efficiency;
Coordinate with the Barangays in the issuance of the notices of delinquencies particularly those addresses which are difficult to locate;
Avail promptly the remedies and apply sanctions as provided in RA 7160 to deter delayed payment and non-payment of taxes; and
The City Assessor to require copy of title upon transfer of property and maintain complete documentation of taxpayer’s record for easy reference.

We reiterated our prior years’ recommendation that the City Mayor require:
The MCCPPEID to -
Reconcile their records with the Accounting Office to determine the causes of discrepancies between their records;
Prepare and submit to the Auditor the revised/corrected RPCPPE after due reconciliations;
The Head, Accounting Office to -
Prepare adjusting entries, if necessary, upon completion of the reconciliation of their records with the inventory report;
Reconcile records of Land Account with the records of the City Treasurer’s   Office and prepare adjusting entries, if necessary; and
The City Appraisal Committees to conduct an appraisal and determine the valuation of the donated property for recording purposes and expedite the titling of the same to prevent third party claims in the future.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the Head, Accounting Office to:
Ensure that no CAs are granted in excess of the maximum cash accountability;
Undertake periodic monitoring of cash accountabilities of the SDOs/DOs and increase the bonds, if necessary;
Instruct the staff assigned in monitoring the CAs to ensure that no CAs are granted in case of existing unliquidated CAs;
Stop the practice of granting multiple CAs;
Determine the whereabouts of former employees and demand the liquidation of their accountabilities;
Enforce strictly the liquidation of CAs within the prescribed period, and ensure that all CAs are liquidated at the end of each year; and
Verify the collectability of unliquidated CAs of more than 10 years, otherwise, request for authority to write-off dormant accounts guided by the conditions and procedures prescribed under COA Circular 
No. 2016-005.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the:
MCCPPEID to:
Complete the inventory-taking of PPE and prepare the RPCPPE by PPE account  and by department/office to facilitate reconciliation of PPE account balances with the accounting records;
Reconcile with the Accounting Office to determine the causes of discrepancies between their records and make the necessary adjustments; and
Prepare and submit the revised/corrected RPCPPE after due reconciliation.
Head, Accounting Office to:
Reconcile the property ledger cards with the records of the MCCPPEID to maintain complete and updated property ledger cards;
Reconcile records of the Land Account with the records of the City Treasurer’s Office;
Verify and analyze the identified discrepancies and errors and make necessary adjustments in the books of accounts;
Compute for the depreciation of the PPE and take up the necessary adjustments to correct the account balances;
City Appraisal Committees to conduct an appraisal and determine the valuation of the donated property for recording purposes and expedite the titling of the same to prevent third party claims in the future;
Head, Engineering Office to:
Conduct the inspection of these structures to determine the current status and its existence;
Conduct appraisal of these structures which may be the basis of recording if documents to support the project cost could no longer be found; and
GSO to maintain Property Cards by class/type of PPE with complete and relevant information as required under the Manual on the New Government Accounting System, among others, the date of acquisition, property number, description, the receipt, disposition, and transfer, and other relevant information to facilitate reconciliation with its own records as well as the accounting records.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the Head, Accounting Office to:
Ensure that no CAs are granted in excess of the maximum cash accountability and that no CAs for special  purposes are granted to those not authorized to handle CAs;
Undertake periodic monitoring  of  cash  accountabilities  of  Special Disbursing Officers (SDOs)/Disbursing Officers (DOs) to determine  the  need to adjust their bonds to ensure the adequacy of their  respective fidelity bonds;
Ensure that no CAs are granted to any SDO/DO in case of existing unliquidated CAs and stop the practice of granting multiple CAs;
Exhaust all possible means to locate the missing payrolls and other documents to facilitate recording of the liquidation;
Determine the whereabouts of former employees and demand the liquidation of their accountabilities;
Enforce strictly the liquidation of CAs within the prescribed period to ensure that all disbursements out of the CAs are recorded in the books;
Verify the  status  of  unliquidated  CAs,   and  if  determined  that liquidation is not possible, request for  an  authority  to  write-off dormant accounts following the guidelines provided under COA  Circular No. 2016-005; and
Review thoroughly the transactions before recording to  ensure  proper account classification and take up the necessary adjusting entries to correct the account balances in the financial statements.

